<h2>Overview</h2><p>In this tutorial, we'll explore the process of reaming the tie rod tapered holes on Reid Racing knuckles to ensure a secure fit for your tie rod ends. If you've recently upgraded your Jeep JK with new knuckles and find that your tie rod ends aren't seating properly, this guide can help you rectify that issue.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>This article will provide a step-by-step breakdown of how to use a reamer bit to adjust the taper on your knuckles, taking into account the specific measurements and dimensions necessary for a perfect fit. We'll discuss the tools you'll need, tips for the best results, and common pitfalls to avoid.</p><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><ol><li><strong>Gather Your Materials</strong>: You'll need a reamer bit, a cordless drill, measuring tools like calipers, and some cutting oil for lubrication.</li><li><strong>Understanding the Dimensions</strong>: Before you start, it's vital to know that the JK tie rod end taper is a 1-in-8 taper, measured at 1.5 inches per foot, and has a specific dimension of 0.640 inches at the small end. Reid Racing knuckles tend to be drilled slightly smaller than this specification, so measuring your knuckle is crucial.</li><li><strong>Preparing to Ream</strong>: Securely mount your knuckle, ensuring it's stable while you work. Make sure the bit is clean and sharp, as a dull bit will make the job harder.</li><li><strong>Reaming Process</strong>: Start drilling slowly and steadily. The recommended method is to cut at half speed and twice the feed rate, allowing for a controlled removal of material. Make sure to measure often to avoid removing too much material.</li><li><strong>Checking the Fit</strong>: After reaming, insert your tie rod end to ensure it fits snugly. You should notice a more secure fit that eliminates any gap left by the original factory drilling. It's often helpful to torque it down and check the fit before finalizing your installation.</li><li><strong>Final Adjustments</strong>: Once satisfied with the fit, reinstall your knuckle, and consider adding red thread lock on the nut to ensure it stays secure during use.</li></ol><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><ul><li>Consider using cutting oil to reduce friction and heat when reaming.</li><li>Take your time! Rushing can lead to mistakes and damage to your knuckles.</li><li>If possible, borrow a reamer bit from a friend or local shop to save costs, but remember, it's best to purchase your own for future projects.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>Reaming the tie rod taper on your Reid Racing knuckles is a straightforward process that can greatly enhance the fitment of your tie rod ends. By careful measurement and a slow, deliberate approach to reaming, you can achieve the desired results and ensure your Jeep is ready for the trails. Remember, an optimal fit is key to steering responsiveness and overall vehicle stability during off-road adventures.</p>

